1
00:00:13,166 --> 00:00:16,800
THIS PROGRAM IS THE RECORD
OF A "BATTLE" AMONGST COMEDIANS.

2
00:00:16,867 --> 00:00:19,767
IN ORDER TO PRESERVE QUALITY,
IT IS MOSTLY UNEDITED.

3
00:00:19,834 --> 00:00:22,433
AS SUCH, VIEWERS MAY ENCOUNTER
EXPLICIT CONTENT.

4
00:00:40,367 --> 00:00:43,033
-Hello, Mr. Matsumoto.
-Hello.

5
00:00:43,567 --> 00:00:47,700
As the creator of this show,
could you tell us what Documental is?

6
00:00:47,767 --> 00:00:49,000
Well...

7
00:00:49,467 --> 00:00:54,000
HITOSHI MATSUMOTO

8
00:00:54,767 --> 00:00:56,967
I had a few ideas for the title.

9
00:00:57,033 --> 00:01:00,667
But long story short,
this is a documentary of sorts.

10
00:01:00,800 --> 00:01:05,834
I wanted to focus on
the mental battle between comedians,

11
00:01:05,967 --> 00:01:08,300
so it's a "Docu-mental."

12
00:01:08,367 --> 00:01:12,467
From "documentary" and "mental"
I ended up with Documental.

13
00:01:13,433 --> 00:01:16,000
DOCUMENTAL

14
00:01:19,367 --> 00:01:23,500
What drove you to create this show
in the first place?

15
00:01:23,567 --> 00:01:25,934
Well, how should I put it?

16
00:01:26,100 --> 00:01:28,467
When you think about what I've done,

17
00:01:29,700 --> 00:01:34,133
I've devoted my whole life to comedy,
ever since I was in elementary school.

18
00:01:34,567 --> 00:01:37,033
This is the train wreck
at the end of the line.

19
00:01:37,367 --> 00:01:42,867
THIS IS HOW FAR COMEDY HAS COME

20
00:01:42,967 --> 00:01:45,467
We've all seen a variety of formats
for comedy.

21
00:01:45,533 --> 00:01:48,400
Sketches, funny stories, funny quizzes,

22
00:01:48,500 --> 00:01:51,934
duo acts, solo acts, stand-up...

23
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:53,600
There are probably more.

24
00:01:53,700 --> 00:01:56,567
But the one format
that hasn't been done is

25
00:01:56,633 --> 00:01:58,500
a "no-holds-barred" show.

26
00:01:58,567 --> 00:02:04,100
A JOURNEY THROUGH UNCHARTED TERRITORY
"THE NO-HOLDS-BARRED SHOW"

27
00:02:04,166 --> 00:02:06,700
The comedians can do whatever they want.

28
00:02:06,934 --> 00:02:09,066
What also makes this unique is:

29
00:02:09,133 --> 00:02:13,400
Comedians usually take turns at making an
audience laugh within a given time frame.

30
00:02:13,467 --> 00:02:15,500
But on this show,

31
00:02:15,567 --> 00:02:19,066
10 comedians are confined to one room.

32
00:02:19,133 --> 00:02:22,266
They have to make the other nine laugh.

33
00:02:22,700 --> 00:02:26,233
But they have to do it
without laughing themselves.

34
00:02:26,500 --> 00:02:29,266
This might actually be the simplest way

35
00:02:29,734 --> 00:02:33,467
and the best way to decide who truly is

36
00:02:33,533 --> 00:02:35,900
the funniest person.

37
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:39,533
THE RAWEST AND MOST DEFINITIVE BATTLE

38
00:02:40,533 --> 00:02:43,700
THE MIGHTIEST

39
00:02:43,834 --> 00:02:46,834
I must admit,
this is sort of an experiment.

40
00:02:47,300 --> 00:02:50,967
A BIG EXPERIMENT

41
00:03:00,467 --> 00:03:02,433
You scared me! Good morning.

42
00:03:03,333 --> 00:03:08,867
THE CHOSEN WARRIORS

43
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:10,367
Mr. Oh.

44
00:03:11,867 --> 00:03:13,433
-Good morning.
-Good morning.

45
00:03:13,600 --> 00:03:15,433
-You have an invitation.
-I do?

46
00:03:17,500 --> 00:03:18,867
This is for you.

47
00:03:24,800 --> 00:03:27,200
-Here you go.
-Oh, thank you.

48
00:03:28,567 --> 00:03:29,500
Good morning.

49
00:03:30,400 --> 00:03:31,667
What is this?

50
00:03:40,133 --> 00:03:41,800
What's going on?

51
00:03:46,734 --> 00:03:48,066
Good morning.

52
00:03:48,166 --> 00:03:49,633
-Good morning.
-Good morning.

53
00:03:50,233 --> 00:03:51,400
Yes?

54
00:03:52,066 --> 00:03:52,934
This is for you.

55
00:03:55,934 --> 00:03:57,467
Does it say "Event"?

56
00:03:58,433 --> 00:04:00,200
-It says "Invitation."
-"Invita-ton"?

57
00:04:06,467 --> 00:04:07,500
Dear sirs,

58
00:04:07,667 --> 00:04:12,433
Now the autumn breeze blows,
the summer heat is but a fond memory.

59
00:04:13,033 --> 00:04:15,400
Have the seasons been treating you well?

60
00:04:15,500 --> 00:04:18,200
I send you this invitation
with my best intentions.

61
00:04:20,667 --> 00:04:25,734
I sincerely hope you will join me
with one million yen on your person.

62
00:04:26,300 --> 00:04:28,633
I am hosting a Documental.

63
00:04:30,500 --> 00:04:32,734
"With one million yen on your person"?

64
00:04:33,567 --> 00:04:34,633
One million yen?

65
00:04:34,700 --> 00:04:35,934
One million yen!

66
00:04:36,700 --> 00:04:40,133
-I have to bring one million yen?
-That's right.

67
00:04:42,500 --> 00:04:46,900
The winner will receive
a 10 million yen reward.

68
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:49,100
To play or not, the choice is yours.

69
00:04:49,500 --> 00:04:51,133
That's too expensive!

70
00:04:52,934 --> 00:04:54,800
One million yen?

71
00:04:55,300 --> 00:04:58,166
If I win, I'll get 10 million yen.
That would be nice.

72
00:04:58,266 --> 00:05:00,066
But I don't really need it.

73
00:05:00,433 --> 00:05:02,867
More importantly,
I don't want to pay one million.

74
00:05:02,934 --> 00:05:07,533
If you don't win, you lose the entry fee?

75
00:05:08,467 --> 00:05:09,700
That's right.

76
00:05:10,500 --> 00:05:12,100
I'll have to think about it.

77
00:05:13,533 --> 00:05:15,867
If you would like to participate,

78
00:05:15,934 --> 00:05:19,300
I will inform you of the time and venue.

79
00:05:19,367 --> 00:05:21,433
I look forward to hearing from you.

80
00:05:22,033 --> 00:05:24,400
The mornings and evenings
are getting chillier.

81
00:05:25,166 --> 00:05:28,900
Please keep yourself in good health.
Yours sincerely,

82
00:05:29,867 --> 00:05:31,567
Hitoshi Matsumoto.

83
00:05:35,934 --> 00:05:37,400
No thanks.

84
00:05:38,033 --> 00:05:40,767
There's no way I could win it.

85
00:05:41,433 --> 00:05:43,800
I'd never win. No way.

86
00:05:44,066 --> 00:05:47,667
This is some grand plan devised
by the comic genius Mr. Matsumoto.

87
00:05:48,133 --> 00:05:50,967
If I just showed up,
they'd tear me to shreds.

88
00:05:53,567 --> 00:05:56,467
Hear that? The sirens are ringing already.

89
00:05:57,433 --> 00:06:02,533
This is like some new kind of scam.
You never say no to Mr. Matsumoto, right?

90
00:06:04,567 --> 00:06:07,567
There are 10 people,
and everyone brings one million.

91
00:06:07,734 --> 00:06:08,700
That's right.

92
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:11,166
And the winner takes 10 million home...

93
00:06:16,967 --> 00:06:19,367
I think I'll laugh right away.

94
00:06:21,367 --> 00:06:22,867
I don't get it.

95
00:06:24,033 --> 00:06:25,734
What's he trying to do?

96
00:06:26,300 --> 00:06:27,100
One million yen?

97
00:06:35,266 --> 00:06:36,900
Wait. What should I do?

98
00:06:39,200 --> 00:06:41,166
This is really going to happen, right?

99
00:06:41,567 --> 00:06:43,300
-It's not a prank?
-It's not.

100
00:06:43,700 --> 00:06:45,600
Another thing is,

101
00:06:46,500 --> 00:06:50,133
I do the TV show You Mustn't Laugh
at the end of each year.

102
00:06:50,433 --> 00:06:53,066
It's become a highly entertaining show

103
00:06:53,133 --> 00:06:57,333
for all ages.

104
00:06:57,400 --> 00:06:59,767
That's great, but it can be limiting.

105
00:07:02,900 --> 00:07:05,066
THE ULTIMATE FIGHT

106
00:07:05,133 --> 00:07:08,166
I wanted to get rid of all the shackles.

107
00:07:08,300 --> 00:07:11,333
AN EXISTENTIAL WORLD OF COMEDY

108
00:07:11,767 --> 00:07:15,467
You know those moments
when you laugh the hardest?

109
00:07:15,533 --> 00:07:18,266
It may be something trivial,
but it hits your funny bone.

110
00:07:18,333 --> 00:07:23,233
I've been wanting to create something
based on that for several years.

111
00:07:23,934 --> 00:07:28,734
THIS IS THE FRONTIER OF COMEDY

112
00:07:28,800 --> 00:07:33,433
There are a tremendous number of
comedians in Japan now.

113
00:07:33,533 --> 00:07:36,834
THEY ARE THE CHOSEN BEASTS

114
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:39,967
It's really like a jungle.

115
00:07:40,333 --> 00:07:42,667
Some comedians do well in the water.

116
00:07:42,734 --> 00:07:44,734
THEY'RE BEASTS IN THE JUNGLE

117
00:07:44,834 --> 00:07:47,333
Some just hang around in trees.

118
00:07:47,633 --> 00:07:49,100
You know what I mean?

119
00:07:49,266 --> 00:07:51,800
Some of them live in swamps.

120
00:07:52,333 --> 00:07:54,700
Some are fast runners...

121
00:07:54,767 --> 00:07:58,233
This show puts a variety of beasts
all in one room.

122
00:07:58,400 --> 00:08:00,200
THE STRONGEST IN THE WILD

123
00:08:00,266 --> 00:08:03,133
So, which of them is the strongest?

124
00:08:03,233 --> 00:08:06,700
I'm sure this won't get
high ratings on TV.

125
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:10,867
Unless you watch pretty carefully,

126
00:08:10,934 --> 00:08:13,300
you won't grasp how funny it is.

127
00:08:13,367 --> 00:08:17,367
You could say it's aimed towards
a very specific audience.

128
00:08:18,633 --> 00:08:23,567
I wouldn't say it's a show for
older people, women, or kids.

129
00:08:23,633 --> 00:08:28,200
But I think those who like it
will be glued to the screen.

130
00:08:28,367 --> 00:08:33,100
So, I think it's not a bad idea
to narrow down our target audience.

131
00:08:33,400 --> 00:08:36,867
After all, it's not easy
to watch videos on Amazon, right?

132
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:41,400
It's too hard for geezers, right?

133
00:08:41,700 --> 00:08:44,467
Subscribing to Amazon is too complicated
for them, right?

134
00:08:44,734 --> 00:08:46,567
Geezers can't do it.

135
00:08:46,834 --> 00:08:50,800
Early elementary kids can't do it, either.

136
00:08:51,100 --> 00:08:54,233
Those people can go elsewhere...

137
00:08:54,567 --> 00:08:55,533
Yeah.

138
00:08:55,600 --> 00:08:57,266
By the way,

139
00:08:57,333 --> 00:09:00,266
I just said comedians were like
animals in the jungle,

140
00:09:00,333 --> 00:09:03,033
and this show is on Amazon, right?

141
00:09:03,834 --> 00:09:07,000
That was either a good joke,
a little confusing, or I got it all wrong.

142
00:09:07,100 --> 00:09:08,567
I'm not sure.

143
00:10:46,367 --> 00:10:51,767
THE COMEDIANS ARRIVE AT THE BATTLEFIELD

144
00:11:10,100 --> 00:11:11,367
Am I the first one?

145
00:11:12,033 --> 00:11:13,100
I'm the first?

146
00:11:13,333 --> 00:11:14,300
Really?

147
00:11:17,400 --> 00:11:19,600
So this is the place.

148
00:11:20,700 --> 00:11:22,166
Where should I sit?

149
00:11:26,500 --> 00:11:29,567
I'm Daisuke Miyagawa. Nice to meet you.

150
00:11:31,533 --> 00:11:34,400
One million yen is a large amount.

151
00:11:36,133 --> 00:11:39,667
I had to think about it at home,
but in the end,

152
00:11:39,834 --> 00:11:41,700
it sounded like fun.

153
00:11:42,266 --> 00:11:45,166
The only problem is,
I don't have any trademark jokes.

154
00:11:45,300 --> 00:11:47,166
I don't have a killer technique.

155
00:11:47,567 --> 00:11:50,700
I don't know how I'm going to fight.

156
00:11:50,867 --> 00:11:53,834
He's an innately happy guy.

157
00:11:54,734 --> 00:11:55,700
How can I put it?

158
00:11:55,767 --> 00:11:57,834
He loves to be around people.

159
00:11:57,900 --> 00:12:01,700
He's the type of guy who always has fun,
whatever he's doing.

160
00:12:01,834 --> 00:12:03,166
HE ENJOYS WHATEVER'S
IN FRONT OF HIM

161
00:12:03,233 --> 00:12:07,867
I think he'll stir things up a lot, but...

162
00:12:09,700 --> 00:12:15,133
Unfortunately, he probably laughs the most
out of the whole group.

163
00:12:15,400 --> 00:12:18,100
QUICK TO LAUGH

164
00:12:18,166 --> 00:12:20,533
I'm scared of the guys who are weird.

165
00:12:20,600 --> 00:12:23,433
I'm not worried about any joke
or gag that's been prepared.

166
00:12:23,633 --> 00:12:26,934
But I'm scared I'll find something funny,
all by myself.

167
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:29,266
Especially when I'm not supposed to laugh.

168
00:12:29,433 --> 00:12:33,467
I'm worried what will happen when
I start to find some trivial thing funny.

169
00:12:34,667 --> 00:12:36,700
That is his weak point.

170
00:12:36,934 --> 00:12:38,600
Do you think he can win?

171
00:12:39,300 --> 00:12:44,033
In terms of making other people laugh,
I think he does have a chance.

172
00:12:44,467 --> 00:12:46,567
It's interesting when you think about it.

173
00:12:46,633 --> 00:12:50,467
If you were to categorize his abilities
and put them in a hexagonal chart,

174
00:12:50,700 --> 00:12:54,633
he excels in one or two areas,
but, overall, it's not well-balanced.

175
00:12:56,000 --> 00:12:58,700
I don't have a strategy to be honest.

176
00:12:59,867 --> 00:13:01,233
I'll see what happens.

177
00:13:01,300 --> 00:13:03,600
It depends on the participants.

178
00:13:05,533 --> 00:13:06,734
I'll sit here.

179
00:13:09,000 --> 00:13:10,266
Wait a minute.

180
00:13:12,667 --> 00:13:14,767
Okay. I will sit here.

181
00:13:27,767 --> 00:13:29,033
Who is it?

182
00:13:41,767 --> 00:13:42,900
Excuse me.

183
00:13:46,734 --> 00:13:48,433
It's Ohchi!

184
00:13:48,800 --> 00:13:50,800
-Good morning.
-Good morning.

185
00:13:51,033 --> 00:13:54,633
I'm Yosuke Ohchi, from the duo Dienoji.
I'm 44 years old.

186
00:13:54,867 --> 00:13:57,867
I have a wife and two daughters.

187
00:13:58,066 --> 00:13:59,300
Nice to meet you.

188
00:13:59,400 --> 00:14:03,934
My wife handed me one million yen
this morning, and now I'm here.

189
00:14:04,200 --> 00:14:05,633
ASKING HIS WIFE FOR THE CASH

190
00:14:05,700 --> 00:14:07,633
Remember that one million yen I mentioned?

191
00:14:07,700 --> 00:14:08,934
Yeah, I do...

192
00:14:09,000 --> 00:14:10,900
Can I have it?

193
00:14:11,100 --> 00:14:12,567
Seriously?

194
00:14:13,600 --> 00:14:15,033
Where will I get that?

195
00:14:16,200 --> 00:14:19,200
My daughter warned me,
"Don't waste our money."

196
00:14:20,433 --> 00:14:22,166
It's Ohchi!

197
00:14:26,567 --> 00:14:27,700
You're gonna sit there?

198
00:14:27,767 --> 00:14:30,200
-Where should I sit?
-Over on the right.

199
00:14:30,300 --> 00:14:34,100
If each of them had to do something
all by themselves,

200
00:14:34,166 --> 00:14:36,533
it wouldn't be funny at all.

201
00:14:36,600 --> 00:14:40,300
Apparently, he's an air guitar champion.

202
00:14:40,367 --> 00:14:41,834
AIR GUITAR WORLD CHAMPION

203
00:14:42,166 --> 00:14:46,233
There's no way he'd win a contest like
that if he was truly a funny comedian.

204
00:14:46,400 --> 00:14:49,867
It's like showing the world
he's not funny.

205
00:14:52,100 --> 00:14:54,934
But he is a go-getter.

206
00:14:55,367 --> 00:14:58,333
It'll be fun to have one guy like him.

207
00:14:58,867 --> 00:15:04,900
However, Ohchi may be
Daisuke's Achilles' heel.

208
00:15:05,834 --> 00:15:07,867
-This is insane.
-It sure is!

209
00:15:08,500 --> 00:15:11,100
-The day has come.
-This is insane.

210
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:18,000
-Know who's coming?
-I have no idea.

211
00:15:18,066 --> 00:15:20,066
-Nobody's said anything.
-Nothing.

212
00:15:24,533 --> 00:15:26,767
I can't believe Daisuke's here.

213
00:15:28,600 --> 00:15:29,533
Someone's coming.

214
00:15:41,200 --> 00:15:42,166
Yes?

215
00:15:42,300 --> 00:15:43,333
Hello?

216
00:15:45,433 --> 00:15:46,633
So it's you?

217
00:15:47,266 --> 00:15:48,266
Someone else from Yoshimoto.

218
00:15:48,333 --> 00:15:49,600
This guy's so annoying.

219
00:15:50,200 --> 00:15:51,567
We're all from Yoshimoto.

220
00:15:51,633 --> 00:15:52,600
Hello.

221
00:15:52,667 --> 00:15:54,333
-Nice seeing you.
-Howdy.

222
00:15:54,467 --> 00:15:57,767
I'm part of the Toro Salmon duo.
I'm Kubota. Nice to meet you.

223
00:15:58,233 --> 00:16:00,700
This guy is...

224
00:16:01,133 --> 00:16:02,633
He's a little...

225
00:16:02,967 --> 00:16:03,934
scary.

226
00:16:05,333 --> 00:16:09,934
He has a bit of a unique style of comedy.

227
00:16:10,133 --> 00:16:11,900
Seaweed. Seaweed. Seaweed.

228
00:16:11,967 --> 00:16:14,600
Is "Seaweed" a palindrome?
No, in reverse it's "Deewaes!"

229
00:16:14,667 --> 00:16:15,400
I don't get it!

230
00:16:15,567 --> 00:16:17,834
And he has what you might call...

231
00:16:18,433 --> 00:16:20,500
a psychopathic streak.

232
00:16:20,600 --> 00:16:21,900
The one million yen?

233
00:16:22,667 --> 00:16:25,166
I paid the entry fee from my savings.

234
00:16:25,266 --> 00:16:27,066
And I borrowed some.

235
00:16:27,133 --> 00:16:30,100
And I participated in a clinical trial
at a university.

236
00:16:30,800 --> 00:16:33,100
Before meds are sold at drug stores,

237
00:16:33,166 --> 00:16:36,000
they're tested out on human subjects.

238
00:16:36,333 --> 00:16:37,600
I made 200,000 yen.

239
00:16:38,934 --> 00:16:42,400
I think rich people will laugh more
because they have fewer worries.

240
00:16:44,000 --> 00:16:48,033
Poor people are defensive,
so they don't laugh much.

241
00:16:48,333 --> 00:16:51,934
To earn one million at Yoshimoto means
I could earn double that elsewhere.

242
00:16:52,166 --> 00:16:54,533
That's enough to retire on in North Korea.

243
00:16:54,600 --> 00:16:57,266
I checked the rules,
and we can use living animals.

244
00:16:57,333 --> 00:16:58,333
ANIMALS ARE PERMITTED

245
00:16:58,400 --> 00:17:01,433
I asked them to bring me
three stray dogs...

246
00:17:02,266 --> 00:17:03,500
It's Kubota...

247
00:17:03,633 --> 00:17:06,266
They're all actually quite happy people.

248
00:17:06,500 --> 00:17:08,066
Why are you wearing a tank top?

249
00:17:08,300 --> 00:17:10,200
I heard we had to wear a collared shirt.

250
00:17:10,467 --> 00:17:12,767
A collared shirt?
Did they prepare one for us?

251
00:17:12,967 --> 00:17:14,767
No, you had to bring your own.

252
00:17:15,000 --> 00:17:16,800
Why did he choose a tank top?

253
00:17:17,066 --> 00:17:20,200
I don't know if I'm hot or cold.
I've thought about this show too much.

254
00:17:20,266 --> 00:17:21,800
He looks like a rickshaw man.

255
00:17:22,100 --> 00:17:23,467
So I stripped.

256
00:17:25,867 --> 00:17:27,000
Kubota is...

257
00:17:27,700 --> 00:17:29,433
He could be dangerous.

258
00:17:30,100 --> 00:17:32,567
-We're all in danger.
-This is dangerous.

259
00:17:35,367 --> 00:17:36,367
No way.

260
00:17:36,567 --> 00:17:37,500
This is bad news.

261
00:17:38,066 --> 00:17:39,266
This is really bad.

262
00:17:42,500 --> 00:17:44,266
Fujimoto makes it a different story.

263
00:17:44,600 --> 00:17:46,100
I'm Fujimoto from Fujiwara.

264
00:17:46,967 --> 00:17:49,133
I will try my bestest!

265
00:17:49,266 --> 00:17:52,734
I simply thought it sounded like fun.

266
00:17:53,500 --> 00:17:54,533
That's all.

267
00:17:54,734 --> 00:17:57,266
In his case,

268
00:17:57,500 --> 00:18:01,567
for every single thing
anybody says or does,

269
00:18:02,100 --> 00:18:04,266
he chips in as the straight man.

270
00:18:04,333 --> 00:18:06,934
-I want your eyes to cave in!
-What the hell!

271
00:18:07,266 --> 00:18:09,100
What kind of insult is that?
"Caved-in eyes"?

272
00:18:09,166 --> 00:18:12,600
His presence could be a problem, too.

273
00:18:12,867 --> 00:18:16,900
The thing is, he plays the straight man,
but he makes funny quips, too.

274
00:18:17,000 --> 00:18:20,200
I think he may cause trouble
for the others.

275
00:18:21,233 --> 00:18:25,066
I'll just deal with whatever unfolds.

276
00:18:25,867 --> 00:18:27,633
That's my only plan.

277
00:18:27,867 --> 00:18:28,633
Yeah.

278
00:18:28,700 --> 00:18:32,633
If Ohchi does something silly,
and Fujimoto starts to play with that,

279
00:18:32,700 --> 00:18:35,033
it will be tough for the others.

280
00:18:35,633 --> 00:18:37,166
My wife said,

281
00:18:38,133 --> 00:18:40,066
"You wanna be on the show, right?

282
00:18:40,667 --> 00:18:42,100
Then go for it."

283
00:18:42,934 --> 00:18:44,600
She was supportive.

284
00:18:44,767 --> 00:18:46,400
And she's the breadwinner anyway.

285
00:18:46,500 --> 00:18:48,300
In fact, it's like...

286
00:18:48,667 --> 00:18:50,533
I can hear a little devil saying,

287
00:18:50,633 --> 00:18:52,834
"It's okay to laugh and lose.
Your wife is rich!"

288
00:18:53,633 --> 00:18:54,600
Right here.

289
00:18:54,700 --> 00:18:56,700
-Is that all you brought?
-Yeah.

290
00:18:57,467 --> 00:18:58,700
How much did you bring?

291
00:18:59,066 --> 00:19:00,433
That's what I brought.

292
00:19:00,633 --> 00:19:02,700
-What did he bring?
-A pouch.

293
00:19:02,800 --> 00:19:05,233
RULE 1: YOU MAY BRING PROPS

294
00:19:05,433 --> 00:19:07,834
-Is that all?
-Your bag is huge!

295
00:19:07,934 --> 00:19:10,567
-You're gonna make us laugh that much?
-No, that's not why...

296
00:19:10,633 --> 00:19:13,066
-What's inside that?
-Isn't that too small?

297
00:19:13,333 --> 00:19:15,266
-What's in it?
-Well...

298
00:19:15,800 --> 00:19:18,500
That's not a bag people take to work.

299
00:19:18,900 --> 00:19:20,633
But, it's...

300
00:19:20,734 --> 00:19:23,967
And this is what it's like
with only four people.

301
00:19:24,700 --> 00:19:26,333
You're not scared of me.

302
00:19:27,000 --> 00:19:29,133
-I didn't expect Daisuke to be here.
-Right?

303
00:19:29,200 --> 00:19:32,333
-I didn't think so, either.
-I thought you were abroad.

304
00:19:32,567 --> 00:19:33,800
I get that a lot.

305
00:19:33,967 --> 00:19:36,266
-You should stay there.
-What does that mean?

306
00:19:36,934 --> 00:19:39,934
Doing overseas reports and eating.
Those jobs suit you.

307
00:19:40,500 --> 00:19:43,333
-What's your problem?
-Go overseas, or to the countryside.

308
00:19:43,934 --> 00:19:45,567
-Look. It's him.
-Uh-oh.

309
00:19:46,500 --> 00:19:47,533
The monster's here.

310
00:19:47,667 --> 00:19:49,233
It's turning into a heavy-weight match.

311
00:19:50,000 --> 00:19:51,600
A monster has arrived.

312
00:19:52,467 --> 00:19:54,066
For real?

313
00:19:55,433 --> 00:19:57,400
I'm Kukky, from Yaseibakudan.

314
00:19:57,667 --> 00:20:00,066
The reason I became a comedian was

315
00:20:00,667 --> 00:20:03,100
I wanted to steal money from
the general public.

316
00:20:03,333 --> 00:20:05,734
I never thought someone would steal
from me.

317
00:20:05,800 --> 00:20:06,700
I said,

318
00:20:06,800 --> 00:20:09,667
"Dude, can you lend me a million yen?"

319
00:20:09,800 --> 00:20:12,900
I borrowed the money from a place called
Yoshimoto Finance.

320
00:20:13,266 --> 00:20:14,500
I signed a lot of papers.

321
00:20:14,633 --> 00:20:16,633
They gave me the loan without any hassle.

322
00:20:16,767 --> 00:20:17,967
It's a very nice company.

323
00:20:18,100 --> 00:20:20,200
The payments get taken out of my salary.

324
00:20:20,266 --> 00:20:21,700
A MILLION YEN LOAN FROM YOSHIMOTO

325
00:20:21,767 --> 00:20:24,333
-I have to pay back 100,000 yen a month?
-Yes.

326
00:20:24,800 --> 00:20:30,400
Well, he is even more of a psychopath.

327
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:33,166
YET ANOTHER PSYCHOPATH

328
00:20:33,533 --> 00:20:35,367
He has a butterfly knife?

329
00:20:36,567 --> 00:20:40,633
If he sets up some kind of trap,

330
00:20:41,200 --> 00:20:43,300
they'll be in trouble indeed.

331
00:20:43,967 --> 00:20:45,700
He's a war veteran!

332
00:20:45,767 --> 00:20:48,600
-Is that a tent?
-Look at Fujimoto's small bag.

333
00:20:49,233 --> 00:20:50,834
I brought 18 robot model kits.

334
00:20:56,166 --> 00:20:57,400
That was a forced punchline.

335
00:20:57,467 --> 00:21:00,600
I think he will do pretty well.

336
00:21:00,900 --> 00:21:04,300
Every time he does something
that seems random,

337
00:21:04,367 --> 00:21:06,767
you start to imagine
what led him to do it.

338
00:21:07,166 --> 00:21:09,767
He can be incredibly funny.

339
00:21:10,467 --> 00:21:11,633
I'll laugh.

340
00:21:12,367 --> 00:21:13,834
I'm already laughing. See?

341
00:21:13,967 --> 00:21:15,767
That's the type of guy I am.

342
00:21:16,000 --> 00:21:18,066
I even laugh at my own jokes.

343
00:21:18,233 --> 00:21:19,300
I'm in trouble.

344
00:21:19,367 --> 00:21:23,600
I'm like canned laughter.
Call me "Can-ghter"

345
00:21:23,867 --> 00:21:26,700
-He means trouble.
-For real? Damn it.

346
00:21:26,867 --> 00:21:29,166
Just make him laugh first.

347
00:21:29,567 --> 00:21:30,433
I'm in trouble.

348
00:21:30,900 --> 00:21:33,200
-These guys crack me up.
-I have a bad feeling.

349
00:21:34,600 --> 00:21:37,533
-I don't like this...
-It feels like we're backstage at Lumine.

350
00:21:37,600 --> 00:21:38,867
Here's another one.

351
00:21:39,734 --> 00:21:41,500
-We got another one.
-I'm done for.

352
00:21:43,467 --> 00:21:45,333
That's the face you'd expect.

353
00:21:46,033 --> 00:21:47,633
-It's him.
-Another dangerous one.

354
00:21:47,900 --> 00:21:49,934
Hi. I am from Japan.

355
00:21:50,467 --> 00:21:51,533
I'm from Trendy Angel.

356
00:21:52,500 --> 00:21:55,000
I think my name is Saito.
Nice to meet you.

357
00:21:55,400 --> 00:21:58,033
I'm this year's "Biggest Hit Comedian."

358
00:21:59,066 --> 00:22:01,633
I've starred in 11 commercials this year.

359
00:22:02,600 --> 00:22:04,934
But I only have 700,000 yen in my account.

360
00:22:11,033 --> 00:22:14,667
I think Saito is the most well-balanced
out of this group.

361
00:22:15,233 --> 00:22:16,567
In many respects.

362
00:22:17,266 --> 00:22:20,567
-He always makes me laugh.
-Stay over there. Next to Ohchi.

363
00:22:21,000 --> 00:22:22,567
-Don't come here.
-Don't say that--

364
00:22:22,633 --> 00:22:24,734
-Oops!
-We haven't started yet.

365
00:22:24,800 --> 00:22:29,700
There are many disadvantages for Saito.

366
00:22:30,700 --> 00:22:33,900
The other nine will never laugh.

367
00:22:34,600 --> 00:22:37,266
at his bald head.

368
00:22:37,834 --> 00:22:38,934
HIS BALDNESS IS LAME

369
00:22:39,000 --> 00:22:40,533
That's a key point.

370
00:22:40,600 --> 00:22:44,533
Women and children might find it funny,
but being bald won't cut it here.

371
00:22:44,867 --> 00:22:47,000
There's no way I'll lose.

372
00:22:48,900 --> 00:22:50,934
-How big is his bag?
-Show us.

373
00:22:51,000 --> 00:22:52,700
-This is it.
-Are you kidding?

374
00:22:52,767 --> 00:22:54,934
-Is that all?
-Look at Fujimoto's.

375
00:22:56,433 --> 00:22:57,834
That's too small.

376
00:22:57,967 --> 00:23:00,500
-What's with that pouch?
-That's your weapon?

377
00:23:00,567 --> 00:23:02,667
New shoes come in bags like that.

378
00:23:02,734 --> 00:23:06,600
Everyone's really happy and smiling now.

379
00:23:06,900 --> 00:23:09,300
The atmosphere's nice and relaxed, but...

380
00:23:10,000 --> 00:23:13,133
For now, they can enjoy themselves,
but soon...

381
00:23:14,100 --> 00:23:16,967
-That's just wrong.
-I was told to wear a collared shirt.

382
00:23:17,033 --> 00:23:19,500
-Then you need a collar.
-Mine has one.

383
00:23:23,767 --> 00:23:26,066
Here's another twisted one.

384
00:23:26,700 --> 00:23:27,800
Too many weirdos.

385
00:23:27,867 --> 00:23:30,133
He's twisted and knotted.

386
00:23:30,200 --> 00:23:32,667
I'm Tenjikunezumi's Kawahara.

387
00:23:32,967 --> 00:23:34,400
I'm looking forward to it.

388
00:23:34,500 --> 00:23:37,233
I went home to think about this properly.

389
00:23:37,300 --> 00:23:39,600
I tried to figure it out.

390
00:23:39,667 --> 00:23:42,300
But even then, I couldn't really get it.

391
00:23:42,500 --> 00:23:44,667
And now, I still don't get it.

392
00:23:44,734 --> 00:23:47,934
He's got peculiarities.

393
00:23:48,934 --> 00:23:50,767
I hope they're not my juniors.

394
00:23:50,867 --> 00:23:52,467
If they're my seniors,

395
00:23:52,834 --> 00:23:55,633
I can give them all I've got.

396
00:23:56,200 --> 00:23:58,400
-We're done for.
-He never shows any emotion.

397
00:23:58,467 --> 00:24:00,834
-Kawahara never laughs.
-You're right.

398
00:24:00,900 --> 00:24:02,033
He's a tough opponent.

399
00:24:02,100 --> 00:24:05,533
He's not the type to pull
a lot of punches.

400
00:24:06,467 --> 00:24:11,166
I don't think he will be dismissed
in the first half.

401
00:24:11,533 --> 00:24:12,967
I can't picture him splitting his sides

402
00:24:13,033 --> 00:24:17,600
with laughter at something somebody does.

403
00:24:18,000 --> 00:24:20,800
Every now and then you'll find
a comedian like that.

404
00:24:21,033 --> 00:24:22,333
Like Itsuji Itao.

405
00:24:22,567 --> 00:24:24,500
THE "ITSUJI ITAO TYPE"

406
00:24:26,000 --> 00:24:27,834
I would like 10 million yen.

407
00:24:27,900 --> 00:24:30,734
But more than that,
I want to leave my mark.

408
00:24:30,867 --> 00:24:35,200
I want to leave a mark worth
one million yen.

409
00:24:37,133 --> 00:24:38,967
You brought enough for a camp.

410
00:24:39,133 --> 00:24:41,900
-All I brought was one big sausage.
-That bombed.

411
00:24:43,100 --> 00:24:47,100
-That bombed as much as your 18 robots.
-No, mine's funnier than a sausage.

412
00:24:50,233 --> 00:24:51,867
He's incredibly expressionless.

413
00:24:51,934 --> 00:24:52,900
Good morning.

414
00:24:56,967 --> 00:24:58,700
I'm Jiro Hachimitsu.

415
00:24:58,800 --> 00:25:03,100
I'll try to take myself into
a state of emptiness.

416
00:25:03,667 --> 00:25:05,200
As empty as possible.

417
00:25:05,767 --> 00:25:07,800
-Good morning.
-I've never seen him laugh.

418
00:25:07,867 --> 00:25:09,800
-He never laughs.
-He does, but...

419
00:25:09,867 --> 00:25:12,200
Yeah, he's not really the type to laugh.

420
00:25:12,333 --> 00:25:16,000
Simply put,
his comedic aptitude is very high.

421
00:25:16,133 --> 00:25:18,600
MR. HIGHLY PROFICIENT

422
00:25:19,367 --> 00:25:22,567
Don't talk about Thomas and Friends now.
There's a subway below us.

423
00:25:22,633 --> 00:25:26,233
He's a straight man who makes funny quips,
but he's different from Fujimoto.

424
00:25:26,300 --> 00:25:29,700
Whenever something happens,
he'll quietly mutter a witty remark.

425
00:25:29,767 --> 00:25:32,734
That's what slowly creeps up on you.

426
00:25:33,133 --> 00:25:34,667
He is a strong opponent.

427
00:25:35,433 --> 00:25:38,600
I was honored.
I accepted the offer right away.

428
00:25:38,734 --> 00:25:42,567
The biggest problem was,
I didn't have a million yen.

429
00:25:42,967 --> 00:25:47,567
My motto is, "Money is not something
you keep overnight."

430
00:25:47,934 --> 00:25:51,467
I have a lot of confidence,
but at the same time,

431
00:25:52,000 --> 00:25:55,600
I laugh easily at the corniest jokes.

432
00:25:56,000 --> 00:25:56,867
I'm in the middle?

433
00:25:56,934 --> 00:25:59,400
Has anyone ever seen Jiro laugh out loud?

434
00:25:59,467 --> 00:26:00,767
-No.
-Never.

435
00:26:01,233 --> 00:26:02,567
All he does is smile.

436
00:26:02,734 --> 00:26:06,266
Now that you mention it,
I've never seen him roll in laughter.

437
00:26:06,367 --> 00:26:08,467
-I laugh at Mr. Bean.
-Mr. Bean?

438
00:26:08,800 --> 00:26:11,300
-Only Mr. Bean?
-Stop trying to make us laugh.

439
00:26:11,600 --> 00:26:14,200
This is an amazing group.

440
00:26:18,433 --> 00:26:19,967
Is it a female contestant?

441
00:26:21,967 --> 00:26:23,633
It's "Thony-An."

442
00:26:24,200 --> 00:26:26,266
We're all from Yoshimoto.

443
00:26:27,867 --> 00:26:29,066
Hello...

444
00:26:30,734 --> 00:26:33,867
Hello. I'm Anthony from the Matenrou duo.

445
00:26:35,133 --> 00:26:38,433
Right now, I'm full of dread.

446
00:26:38,934 --> 00:26:40,800
And this guy...

447
00:26:42,233 --> 00:26:46,033
I think his career is a lot shorter
than the others.

448
00:26:46,133 --> 00:26:49,633
If he doesn't hold back
in front of his seniors,

449
00:26:49,734 --> 00:26:52,400
he might do well...

450
00:26:52,500 --> 00:26:54,367
But, Anthony?

451
00:26:54,734 --> 00:26:58,033
I think he might hold back a little
out of respect for his seniors.

452
00:26:58,200 --> 00:27:00,300
Last month I earned 220,000 yen.

453
00:27:00,400 --> 00:27:03,567
I borrowed 500,000 yen
from my senior colleagues.

454
00:27:04,900 --> 00:27:06,767
Thank you so much, BKB.

455
00:27:06,900 --> 00:27:09,133
I don't want to regret lending you this.

456
00:27:09,200 --> 00:27:12,033
Make me glad that I lent it to you.

457
00:27:12,133 --> 00:27:13,633
-Certainly.
-Keep that in mind.

458
00:27:14,600 --> 00:27:16,600
-I'm sure you have the money.
-I don't.

459
00:27:16,967 --> 00:27:18,133
Stop acting poor.

460
00:27:18,800 --> 00:27:20,633
Thank you for lending me the money.

461
00:27:21,367 --> 00:27:24,667
I borrowed from my mom as well,
and I finally raised one million.

462
00:27:25,133 --> 00:27:28,734
He's the only one not fully Japanese,
so it'll be interesting.

463
00:27:31,834 --> 00:27:35,667
But when it comes to these guys,
it's like what I said about Saito.

464
00:27:36,633 --> 00:27:40,400
They won't laugh at his usual jokes.
Not when he only looks a bit different.

465
00:27:41,233 --> 00:27:44,934
When I first got to quit my part-time job
after becoming a comedian,

466
00:27:45,533 --> 00:27:47,800
I was so happy.

467
00:27:47,934 --> 00:27:50,567
I never want to have
a part-time job again.

468
00:27:51,166 --> 00:27:53,767
But if I lose this,
I'll have to find a part-time job.

469
00:27:55,200 --> 00:27:56,533
You look like a backpacker.

470
00:27:58,633 --> 00:27:59,867
Where'd he come from?

471
00:28:00,166 --> 00:28:03,767
-Stop making funny quips.
-Why? We haven't started yet.

472
00:28:04,967 --> 00:28:06,400
He looks like a hitchhiker.

473
00:28:06,900 --> 00:28:08,533
So there are nine.

474
00:28:08,633 --> 00:28:11,033
We have nine participants now.

475
00:28:11,567 --> 00:28:14,367
That means there's one more.

476
00:28:15,166 --> 00:28:16,600
One more.

477
00:28:17,967 --> 00:28:19,800
Who is the last participant?

478
00:28:25,867 --> 00:28:27,667
I'm sure it's someone from Yoshimoto.

479
00:28:30,400 --> 00:28:32,200
-No way.
-The worst participant!

480
00:28:33,400 --> 00:28:35,834
-Oh, no!
-This is terrible!

481
00:28:37,767 --> 00:28:38,900
I'm Jimmy Onishi.

482
00:28:39,333 --> 00:28:41,533
I'm just going to try my best.

483
00:28:41,700 --> 00:28:43,867
He is a monster.

484
00:28:46,433 --> 00:28:50,166
The nine others are not going to like it.

485
00:28:51,467 --> 00:28:53,000
Not with him here.

486
00:28:53,567 --> 00:28:55,900
The consumer loan officer told me
I can't borrow a million yen.

487
00:28:56,767 --> 00:28:58,934
Because my annual income is only
six million.

488
00:28:59,033 --> 00:29:04,834
It really hit me how low
my standing is in society.

489
00:29:05,367 --> 00:29:06,633
He laughs easily.

490
00:29:09,800 --> 00:29:13,266
All it would take is one
really simple dirty joke.

491
00:29:13,500 --> 00:29:14,867
He's that stupid.

492
00:29:15,166 --> 00:29:17,600
Well, you see...

493
00:29:17,667 --> 00:29:20,734
Dumb luck always plays a part in comedy.

494
00:29:20,800 --> 00:29:22,734
I'm going to aim for dumb luck.

495
00:29:23,667 --> 00:29:24,834
He's already won.

496
00:29:24,934 --> 00:29:26,266
Look how grey his hair is.

497
00:29:27,166 --> 00:29:29,066
-Stop saying things like that.
-Why?

498
00:29:29,166 --> 00:29:30,333
Stop it.

499
00:29:30,433 --> 00:29:33,433
This is really going to be something.

500
00:29:55,767 --> 00:29:59,367
They are quite an elite troop.

501
00:29:59,600 --> 00:30:01,767
THE ELITE TROOP

502
00:30:01,867 --> 00:30:03,800
I think this will be great.

503
00:30:05,100 --> 00:30:06,133
This is not good.

504
00:30:06,200 --> 00:30:09,066
-With him here...
